<div class="indented"><a id="comment-4422196"></a>


<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-4422196">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Mon, 02/10/2014 - 21:45 | <a href="/news/2014-02-10/saxo-bank-ceo-bitcoin-faces-serious-challenges-needs-link-real-assets#comment-4422196" class="active">4422196</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/buckaroo-banzai" title="View user profile.">Buckaroo Banzai</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/buckaroo-banzai" title="View user profile."><img src="http://www.zerohedge.com/sites/default/files/pictures/picture-14002.jpg" alt="Buckaroo Banzai&#039;s picture" title="Buckaroo Banzai&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>Actually, you are quite wrong.</p>
<p>"Money" is defined as anything that embodies at least one, and preferably (but not necessarily) all three of the following characteristics:</p>
<p>1) store of value<br />
2) medium of exchange (aka "currency"<br />
3) unit of account</p>
<p>Gold, dollars, and BitCoin can all be considered "money".</p>
<p>It is worth noting that nothing currently in use fulfills all three of these characteristics. Dollars are the closest, but as we know, they are a poor store of value.</p>

  </div>
  <div class="links"><ul class="links"><li class="comment_forbidden first last"></li>
</ul></div>
